arch:note.arch:string: The purpose of the daily journal was to record the activities taking place in a trench each day. This included which loci were excavated, how and why loci were excavated and the ongoing impressions of the relationships among loci. It should be noted that journals record the actions, impressions and ideas of trench supervisors during the excavations. They are not, therefore, the final interpretations or syntheses of the emerging data.

arch:internalDocument.arch:string:
Daily Trench Journal

Area F, Trench 7

June 14, 2005

C. Painter

Today the primary concentration was on leveling loci 7177, 7179, and 7180 by excavating roughly 10cm throughout with a combination of hand picks, trowels and shovels so that these loci can be closed. This final leveling of these areas is considered to be the basal levels of the building phase that included structure 7178, pit 7181, bin/pit 7186 and mud brick platform 7183.

Leveling was also performed in L7191 which revealed a compacted dirt surface with some flat-lying pot sherds and up to 5cm rounded pebbles. This surface comes up to the western edge of a new mud brick wall that will be assigned a locus number as soon as it is better defined. Same is true of the compacted surface and a second surface which emerged at the end of the day below the first surface. This second surface is also compacted but with a thin layer of white/gray plastering that is associated with a grinder fragment that is either overturned or was used in a secondary context as a door socket as there is a small indentation on the top.

At the same time, walls 7163 and 7154 were both removed. Subwall fill locus 7197 was assigned below 7163 as a reddish yellow (7.5 YR 6/6) medium to fine textures fill with an ashy fine matrix. A partially preserved vessel was uncovered in this locus, photographed, and removed as a separate KT (KT3). The subwall fill below wall 7154 was assigned as L7198 and was a light reddish brown (5 YR 6/3) coarse angular fill with <5 cm clay clumps and mud brick debris. Both walls and fills were excavated using a combination of large pick ax and small hand pick.

Lastly a number of new loci were opened in the western half of the trench as vigorous cleaning and scrapping two days ago revealed a number of new features. To open new loci required first that fill L7173 be closed so bottom elevations were taken. Then I opened first pit L7199, a dark gray (10 YR 4/1) fine ashy matrix locus with clay clumps and pebbles. Directly south and abutting this pit is burial L7200. This locus is composed of a dark yellowish brown (10 YR 4/4) medium to coarse sandy matrix pit that is lined on the north, east and south sides by three separate mud bricks, each roughly 30-40 cm in length and poorly preserved. The body itself resides within this mud brick lining and appears to be a small child based on the teeth and surrounding bones. Unfortunately the individual is poorly preserved and highly disturbed though further articulation may prove that the majority of the skeleton is still intact.

The final two loci to be opened today were two wall features, one located in the southwest corner of the trench. This mud brick feature, assigned locus 7201, is composed of two walls with pinkish (7.5 YR 7/4) bricks that come together to form a corner. A north-south running walls projects north out of the southern baulk meeting another east-west running wall that projects to the west. The number of courses and rows will be determined later as I investigate further in this area. As it stands now, there is much mud brick debris in the surrounding area and it will be critical to separate the fill from the actual wall. Thankfully on the southern "interior" side of this feature is an ashy/pit-like area which is easily distinguishable from the walls themselves.

L7202 is another wall located in the northwest corner of the trench directly below subwall fill L7197. This mud brick wall is actually the same wall that has been visible in the western section profile of pit 7162 for some time resting below wall 7164 and a small ash layer. Another indication for the presence of this wall is the presence of an ashy/pit-like area that is abutting 7202 on its northern side and forming a relatively straight line all the way west into the western baulk. This and the entire western area of the trench will be explored further in the coming days.
